            "storyinfo": "West Antarctica has thinner ice than East Antarctica and there are ice sheets on the bedrock thatâ€™s below sea level. This makes West Antarctica unstable. The ocean currents transports the water underneath the ice sheets and when currents start to transport warmer, salty water, the ice will start to melt. The ice contains freshwater, meaning that the melted water will contain less salt and also be colder when mixed. The newly melted water will then be transported out to the oceans and leading to sea level rise.",
